    "updated_at": "2012-01-20T01:45:50Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Hold on, I'm not so sure we want this: relative `from .` imports make it easier to move code around and refactor, so there's a price for this.  IMO, python 3.2 is really the first 'viable' python3.x version worth putting serious effort into, as I don't think there are many production houses who have switched to 3.x yet can't use 3.2.  Given how this is actually a bug in python 3.1 and that catering to it would have a cost for us, my opinion is that it's simply not worth it.\n"
  },
